Subject to the terms and conditions of this License, each contributor hereby grants to You a worldwide, royalty-free, non-exclusive, irrevocable license to:

	•	Copy and distribute verbatim copies of the Program's source code and object code as you receive it;
	•	Study and understand how the Program works;
	•	Modify the Program or any portion of it, thus forming a Derivative Work;
	•	Distribute copies of such Derivative Works to the public, provided the conditions in this License are met;

THIS GRANT IS CONDITIONED UPON YOUR STATUS AS A PERMITTED ENTITY AND YOUR COMPLIANCE WITH ALL TERMS OF THIS LICENSE. If you are not a Permitted Entity, you are not granted any rights under this License and may not use, copy, modify, or distribute the Program.

SECTION 3 — CIVIC USE RESTRICTION

The rights granted in Section 2 are expressly limited to Permitted Entities as defined in Section 1. This License does not grant any rights to use the Program for Commercial Use by for-profit entities.

Specifically, the following are PROHIBITED under this License:

	•	Use, deployment, integration, or distribution of the Program by a for-profit private corporation, limited liability company, partnership, or similar entity organized primarily for commercial purposes;
	•	Sale of the Program itself, or of any service whose value derives primarily from providing access to the Program, for commercial profit;
	•	Incorporation of the Program, in whole or in part, into proprietary commercial software products;
	•	Use of the Program to provide commercial Software-as-a-Service (SaaS) to paying customers, except by Permitted Entities providing such services to citizens or government bodies for civic purposes.

For the avoidance of doubt: a private contractor or vendor hired by a Permitted Entity to deploy or maintain the Program solely on behalf of that Permitted Entity may do so, provided the contractor does not claim independent rights to the Program and does not use the Program for any other commercial purpose.

If You are uncertain whether Your use qualifies as permitted, You should seek a written determination from the original copyright holders, legal representation of the contributors or the designated successor entity for the stewardship of the Program.

SECTION 4 — VERBATIM COPYING

You may copy and distribute verbatim copies of the Program's source code as you receive it, in any medium, provided that you conspicuously and appropriately publish on each copy:

(a) An appropriate copyright notice;
(b) A disclaimer of warranty as set forth in Section 10;
(c) A copy of or reference to this License;
(d) A clear statement that the Program is Civic Software governed by the Civic Innovation License v1.0 and subject to civic use restrictions.

You may charge a reasonable fee for the physical or electronic act of transferring or hosting a copy. You may not charge a license fee for the rights granted under this License. You may, however, offer support, maintenance, or implementation services for a fee, provided You are a Permitted Entity and such services are offered in furtherance of civic purposes.

SECTION 5 — MODIFICATIONS AND DERIVATIVE WORKS

You may modify your copy or copies of the Program or any portion of it, forming Derivative Works, and copy and distribute such modifications or Derivative Works under the terms of Section 4 above, provided that you also meet all of the following conditions:

(a) You must cause the modified files to carry prominent notices stating that you changed the files and the date of any change;
(b) You must cause any work that you distribute or publish that in whole or in part contains or is derived from the Program, to be licensed as a whole at no charge to all third parties under the terms of this License;
(c) If the modified Program normally reads commands interactively when run, you must cause it, when started running for such interactive use in the most ordinary way, to print or display an announcement including an appropriate copyright notice and a notice that there is no warranty (or that you provide a warranty), and that this program is Civic Software distributed under the Civic Innovation License, and how users can view a copy of this License;
(d) The Derivative Work must remain Civic Software and must not be relicensed under any license that removes the civic use restrictions or the copyleft obligations of this License;
(e) Derivative Works must be distributed only to Permitted Entities.

These requirements apply to the modified work as a whole. If identifiable sections of that work are not derived from the Program, and can be reasonably considered independent and separate works in themselves, then this License does not apply to those sections when you distribute them as separate works. But when you distribute the same sections as part of a whole that is a Derivative Work, the entire work must be licensed under this License.

SECTION 6 — DISTRIBUTION IN OBJECT CODE OR EXECUTABLE FORM

You may copy and distribute the Program (or a Derivative Work under Section 5) in object code or executable form under the terms of Sections 4 and 5, provided that you also:

(a) Accompany it with the complete corresponding machine-readable source code, which must be distributed under the terms of Sections 4 and 5 above; or
(b) Accompany it with a written offer, valid for at least three years, to give any third party — for no charge beyond the reasonable cost of physically performing the distribution — a complete machine-readable copy of the corresponding source code; or
(c) Accompany it with the information you received as to the offer to distribute the corresponding source code (this option is permitted only for non-commercial distribution and only if you received the Program in object code or executable form with such an offer).

Source code distributed under this section must be under the terms of this License, and must include all the materials needed to modify and compile the object code.

SECTION 7 — NETWORK USE AND SERVICE DEPLOYMENT

If you run a modified version of the Program on a server or in a networked environment and allow other parties to interact with it remotely through a computer network, you must make the complete corresponding source code of your modified version available to those users under the terms of this License.

This obligation applies whether or not You distribute the Program. The purpose of this provision is to ensure that civic communities retain access to improvements made to their software even when it is deployed as a service rather than distributed as software. This section constitutes an affirmative software freedom guarantee for networked civic software.

You must make the source code available through a publicly accessible repository (such as a government code repository, a civic code commons, or a public version control platform), and must prominently disclose the location of this repository to all users of the service.

